  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">2018 Nigeria Floods</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Nigeria has experienced continued rainfall since July. The rains have left approximately 80% of the country flooded and Nigeria s two major rivers Niger River and Benue River have overflowed into the surrounding communities. Many states have been affected with unprecedented high-water levels. The Government of Nigeria announced a state of emergency in the four worst affected states of Kogi Niger Anambra and Delta. The flood alert released by Nigeria Hydrological Services Agency (NIHSA) indicated that states and communities by the banks of River Niger and Benue may experience further flooding due to a systematic daily rise in the water levels from both major rivers that cut Nigeria into almost two equal parts: Niger and Benue. In addition more rainfall has been predicted. States that are at risk or further risk are those adjacent to River Niger and Benue which are Kebbi Niger Kwara Kogi Edo Anambra Rivers Delta Bayelsa Adamawa Taraba Benue and Nasarawa.</narrative>
  </description>
